# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition of a Queue

> [!NOTE]
> **Queue (KTU 2024 Scheme Definition):** A **Queue** is a linear, ordered data structure that adheres strictly to the **FIFO (First In, First Out)** principle. Insertion of elements is permitted only at one end called the **REAR** (or **BACK** / **TAIL**), and deletion is permitted only at the opposite end called the **FRONT** (or **HEAD**). It is formally a special case of the more general **ADT (Abstract Data Type)** that models the concept of a waiting line.

The two principal operations are universally named:
- **Enqueue** : The process of adding an element to the **rear** of the queue.
- **Dequeue** : The process of removing an element from the **front** of the queue.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight (KTU Module 2):** Students must understand queue implementation using **arrays** (static, fixed-size), implementation using **linked lists** (dynamic, pointer-based), the special **circular queue** variant (eliminates memory wastage of linear queue), and the **priority queue** variant (where ordering is based on priority, not arrival time).

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Movie Ticket Counter"

Imagine you and your friends arrive at a movie theater to buy tickets. There is only **one** ticket counter, and a single line forms in front of it. Consider the following real-world situation:

1. **Person A** arrives first and stands at the front of the line.
2. **Person B** arrives next and stands immediately **behind** Person A.
3. **Person C** arrives and stands behind Person B.

The counter opens. Who gets served first? Naturally, **Person A** — the person who has been waiting the longest. After Person A is served and leaves, **Person B** moves to the front, and so on.

> The principle is exactly the same in a queue data structure: **the element that was inserted first is the element that gets removed first.** In Computer Science terminology, this is called **FIFO ordering**.

Other real-world queue analogies include:
- **CPU scheduling** in Operating Systems (process ready queue).
- **Print spooler** in a networked office (first print job sent, first printed).
- **Breadth-First Search (BFS)** in graph traversal.
- **Customer service call centers** (calls answered in the order they arrive, ignoring queue jumping).
- **Network buffers** (routers buffer packets and forward them in arrival order).

> [!NOTE]
> **Standard Metrics (KTU Notation):**
> - **Time Complexity** of basic queue operations is **O(1)** for **Enqueue**, **Dequeue**, **Front**, and **Rear** (in linked list implementation).
> - **Space Complexity** of a queue of *n* elements is **O(n)** in the worst case.
> - The standard term for an empty queue is **UNDERFLOW** condition.
> - The standard term for a full queue (in array-based implementation) is **OVERFLOW** condition.

## 1.3 Why Study Queues?

Queues are not merely an academic curiosity — they are the **backbone of asynchronous system design**:

- **Buffering in I/O systems** (keyboard input, network packets).
- **Resource scheduling** in operating systems (FCFS, Round-Robin).
- **Message brokers** in distributed systems (RabbitMQ, Kafka).
- **Simulation of real-world systems** (bank queues, traffic flow).
- **Algorithm design** (BFS, level-order tree traversal, topological sort).

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Primitive Operations on a Queue (ADT Specification)

The Abstract Data Type specification of a queue (per KTU Module 2 expected question pattern) is formally defined as follows. Let **Q** denote a queue, **x** denote an element, and let the queue be of maximum capacity **N** (for array-based) or unbounded (for linked-list-based).

| # | Operation | Formal Specification | Pre-condition | Post-condition |
|---|-----------|----------------------|---------------|----------------|
| 1 | **enqueue(Q, x)** | Insert *x* at the rear of *Q* | !isFull(Q) | *x* becomes the new rear; size increases by 1 |
| 2 | **dequeue(Q)** | Remove and return the front element of *Q* | !isEmpty(Q) | Front element is removed; size decreases by 1 |
| 3 | **front(Q) / peek(Q)** | Return (without removing) the front element | !isEmpty(Q) | Queue is unchanged |
| 4 | **rear(Q)** | Return (without removing) the rear element | !isEmpty(Q) | Queue is unchanged |
| 5 | **isEmpty(Q)** | Return true if *Q* has no elements | None | Returns Boolean |
| 6 | **isFull(Q)** | Return true if *Q* cannot accept more elements | None | Returns Boolean (array-based only) |
| 7 | **size(Q)** | Return the number of elements in *Q* | None | Returns Integer $\geq 0$ |

## 2.2 Boundary Conditions — The "Why" and the "How"

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Concept:** The boundary conditions of a queue are the **most frequently asked** topic in 2-mark and 3-mark KTU questions. Memorize these conditions verbatim.

### 2.2.1 Linear Queue (Array Implementation)

Let **MAX** be the maximum capacity of the queue, **front** index the position of the first element, and **rear** index the position of the last element. Initial state: `front = -1`, `rear = -1`.

- **Underflow Condition (Empty Queue):** `front == -1` **OR** `front > rear`
- **Overflow Condition (Full Queue):** `rear == MAX - 1`
- **Enqueue Operation:** `rear = rear + 1`, then `Q[rear] = x`. If first insertion, set `front = 0`.
- **Dequeue Operation:** `x = Q[front]`, then `front = front + 1`. If queue becomes empty, reset `front = rear = -1`.

### 2.2.2 The Critical Drawback of Linear Queue — "Memory Wastage"

Suppose **MAX = 5**, and we have performed these operations:
1. Enqueue 5 elements: 10, 20, 30, 40, 50 → **rear = 4**
2. Dequeue 3 elements → **front = 3**
3. Now the array has 2 valid elements (40, 50) at indices 3 and 4, but **front = 3, rear = 4**.
4. Try to enqueue one more element → it will be **rejected as OVERFLOW**, even though indices 0, 1, 2 are **completely empty**.

> This wasted space is the **primary motivation** for the **Circular Queue** design.

### 2.2.3 Circular Queue (Array Implementation)

A circular queue treats the array as a **ring** (modulo MAX arithmetic), so empty cells from the front can be reused.

- **Empty Condition:** `front == -1`
- **Full Condition:** `(rear + 1) % MAX == front`
- **Enqueue:** `rear = (rear + 1) % MAX`, then `Q[rear] = x`. If first insertion, set `front = 0`.
- **Dequeue:** `x = Q[front]`. If `front == rear`, reset `front = rear = -1`. Else, `front = (front + 1) % MAX`.

### 2.2.4 Priority Queue

A priority queue is a queue in which each element has an associated **priority value**. When dequeuing, the element with the **highest priority** is removed first (in a *max-priority queue*); in a *min-priority queue*, the lowest-priority element is removed first.

- Two common internal implementations:
  1. **Unsorted array/linked list** : enqueue is O(1), dequeue is O(n) (linear search for highest priority).
  2. **Sorted array/linked list** : enqueue is O(n) (insertion in sorted order), dequeue is O(1).
  3. **Binary heap** (advanced) : both enqueue and dequeue are O(log n).

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> **The following table is a high-yield cheat sheet** for the KTU Module 2 examination. All boundary conditions and complexity formulas are summarized below. **Important LaTeX rule:** Absolute value bars are written as `\vert` or `\mid`, **not** the literal `|` character, to preserve markdown table integrity.

| Data Structure Variant | Empty Condition | Full Condition | Enqueue Time | Dequeue Time | Space Wastage? |
|------------------------|-----------------|----------------|--------------|--------------|----------------|
| **Linear Queue (Array, MAX = N)** | `front == -1` | `rear == N - 1` | O(1) | O(1) | Yes (cannot reuse freed cells) |
| **Circular Queue (Array, MAX = N)** | `front == -1` | `(rear + 1) % N == front` | O(1) | O(1) | No (wraps around) |
| **Linked-List Queue** | `front == NULL` | Never full (until memory exhausted) | O(1) | O(1) | No (dynamic allocation) |
| **Priority Queue (Unsorted Array)** | `size == 0` | `size == N - 1` | O(1) | O(n) | Same as array |
| **Priority Queue (Sorted Array)** | `size == 0` | `size == N - 1` | O(n) | O(1) | Same as array |
| **Priority Queue (Binary Heap)** | `size == 0` | `size == N - 1` | O(log n) | O(log n) | Same as array |

**Position Update Formulas (Circular Queue):**

$$
\text{next\_rear} = (\text{rear} + 1) \bmod \text{MAX}
$$

$$
\text{next\_front} = (\text{front} + 1) \bmod \text{MAX}
$$

**Queue Size Formula (Circular Queue, with MAX = N):**

$$
\text{size} = (\text{rear} - \text{front} + N) \bmod N
$$

> The use of **modulo arithmetic** in the size formula is essential because, in a circular queue, `rear` may be numerically **less than** `front` (since indices wrap around). The **+ N** term compensates for this wrap-around, ensuring the result is always a non-negative integer.

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Operating Systems (OS)**: The **Ready Queue** in process schedulers is typically a circular queue, ensuring fair CPU time allocation.
- **Networking**: The **packet buffer** in network routers uses a circular queue to handle bursty traffic.
- **Embedded Systems**: Real-time operating systems (RTOS) use priority queues for **task scheduling** based on urgency.
- **Computer Graphics**: **Painter's algorithm** for hidden surface removal uses priority queues.
- **Data Compression**: **Huffman coding** uses a min-priority queue (min-heap) to build the optimal prefix code tree.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations, Implementations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Linear Queue Implementation Using Arrays (Exhaustive C++ Program)

> [!NOTE]
> The following is the **complete, exam-ready C++ implementation** of a linear queue using an array. The KTU 2024 Scheme typically asks for either the **enqueue/dequeue logic** or the **full program** as a 7-mark or 14-mark question.

### 3.1.1 Program Structure (Class Definition)

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#define MAX 100
using namespace std;

class Queue {
private:
    int arr[MAX];
    int front, rear;

public:
    // Constructor: Initialize an empty queue
    Queue() {
        front = -1;
        rear  = -1;
    }

    // Check if the queue is empty
    bool isEmpty() {
        return (front == -1 || front > rear);
    }

    // Check if the queue is full
    bool isFull() {
        return (rear == MAX - 1);
    }

    // Enqueue: Insert element x at the rear
    void enqueue(int x) {
        if (isFull()) {
            cout << "Queue Overflow! Cannot enqueue " << x << endl;
            return;
        }
        if (front == -1)       // First element insertion
            front = 0;
        rear = rear + 1;
        arr[rear] = x;
        cout << x << " enqueued successfully." << endl;
    }

    // Dequeue: Remove and return the front element
    int dequeue() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Queue Underflow! Nothing to dequeue." << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        int x = arr[front];
        front = front + 1;
        // Reset when queue becomes empty after dequeue
        if (front > rear)
            front = rear = -1;
        return x;
    }

    // Peek: Return the front element without removing
    int peek() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Queue is empty." << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        return arr[front];
    }

    // Display: Print all elements from front to rear
    void display() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Queue is empty." << endl;
            return;
        }
        cout << "Queue (front to rear): ";
        for (int i = front; i <= rear; i++)
            cout << arr[i] << " ";
        cout << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Queue q;
    q.enqueue(10);
    q.enqueue(20);
    q.enqueue(30);
    q.display();
    cout << "Front element: " << q.peek() << endl;
    cout << "Dequeued: " << q.dequeue() << endl;
    q.display();
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.1.2 Step-by-Step Trace of Operations

Suppose we execute the following sequence on a fresh queue (MAX = 5, initial `front = -1`, `rear = -1`):

| Step | Operation | State Before | Decision Branch Taken | State After |
|------|-----------|--------------|-----------------------|-------------|
| 1 | `enqueue(10)` | `front=-1, rear=-1` | First insertion → `front=0` | `front=0, rear=0, arr[0]=10` |
| 2 | `enqueue(20)` | `front=0, rear=0` | Normal insertion | `front=0, rear=1, arr[1]=20` |
| 3 | `enqueue(30)` | `front=0, rear=1` | Normal insertion | `front=0, rear=2, arr[2]=30` |
| 4 | `dequeue()` | `front=0, rear=2` | Returns `arr[0]=10` | `front=1, rear=2` |
| 5 | `enqueue(40)` | `front=1, rear=2` | Normal insertion | `front=1, rear=3, arr[3]=40` |
| 6 | `dequeue()` | `front=1, rear=3` | Returns `arr[1]=20` | `front=2, rear=3` |
| 7 | `enqueue(50)` | `front=2, rear=3` | Normal insertion | `front=2, rear=4, arr[4]=50` |
| 8 | `enqueue(60)` | `front=2, rear=4` | `rear == MAX-1` → **OVERFLOW** | No change |

> **Critical observation**: After Step 8, the array still has **two empty cells** at indices 0 and 1, yet the queue reports **OVERFLOW**. This is the **wastage problem** of the linear queue.

## 3.2 Circular Queue Implementation Using Arrays (Exhaustive C++ Program)

### 3.2.1 Why the Circular Queue Solves the Wastage Problem

By using **modulo arithmetic** (i.e., `% MAX`), the `rear` index **wraps around** to 0 after reaching `MAX - 1`. This allows the queue to reuse the previously freed cells at the front of the array.

### 3.2.2 Full C++ Implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#define MAX 5
using namespace std;

class CircularQueue {
private:
    int arr[MAX];
    int front, rear;

public:
    CircularQueue() {
        front = -1;
        rear  = -1;
    }

    bool isEmpty() {
        return (front == -1);
    }

    bool isFull() {
        return ((rear + 1) % MAX == front);
    }

    void enqueue(int x) {
        if (isFull()) {
            cout << "Circular Queue Overflow!" << endl;
            return;
        }
        if (front == -1)        // First element
            front = 0;
        rear = (rear + 1) % MAX;
        arr[rear] = x;
        cout << x << " enqueued." << endl;
    }

    int dequeue() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Circular Queue Underflow!" << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        int x = arr[front];
        if (front == rear) {     // Only one element was present
            front = rear = -1;
        } else {
            front = (front + 1) % MAX;
        }
        return x;
    }

    void display() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Queue is empty." << endl;
            return;
        }
        cout << "Circular Queue: ";
        int i = front;
        while (true) {
            cout << arr[i] << " ";
            if (i == rear) break;
            i = (i + 1) % MAX;
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
};
```

### 3.2.3 Step-by-Step Trace Demonstrating the Wrap-Around

Let **MAX = 5**, initial state `front = -1, rear = -1`. Execute:

| Step | Operation | front | rear | Array Contents (Logical View) | Notes |
|------|-----------|-------|------|--------------------------------|-------|
| 1 | enqueue(10) | 0 | 0 | [10, _, _, _, _] | First insertion, front becomes 0 |
| 2 | enqueue(20) | 0 | 1 | [10, 20, _, _, _] | Normal |
| 3 | enqueue(30) | 0 | 2 | [10, 20, 30, _, _] | Normal |
| 4 | dequeue() | 1 | 2 | [_, 20, 30, _, _] | Removes 10 |
| 5 | dequeue() | 2 | 2 | [_, _, 30, _, _] | Removes 20 |
| 6 | enqueue(40) | 2 | 3 | [_, _, 30, 40, _] | Normal |
| 7 | enqueue(50) | 2 | 4 | [_, _, 30, 40, 50] | Normal |
| 8 | enqueue(60) | 2 | 0 | [60, _, 30, 40, 50] | **Wrap-around!** rear = (4+1)%5 = 0 |
| 9 | dequeue() | 3 | 0 | [60, _, _, 40, 50] | Removes 30 |

> **Key Takeaway:** At Step 8, the linear queue would have reported **OVERFLOW** (since `rear == MAX - 1`). The circular queue, however, **wraps `rear` back to 0** and successfully inserts 60 at index 0. The freed cells from dequeue operations are now **reused**, eliminating memory wastage.

### 3.2.4 Why `(rear + 1) % MAX == front` Indicates Full

In a circular queue of size MAX, we can store at most **MAX - 1** elements (not MAX). The reasoning:

- If we allowed MAX elements, then `rear == front` would be **ambiguous** — it could mean either empty OR full.
- By sacrificing one slot to act as a **sentinel**, we can distinguish:
  - `front == -1` → **Empty**
  - `(rear + 1) % MAX == front` → **Full**
  - `front != -1` and the above is false → **Partially Full**

> Alternative design: Maintain a separate `count` variable to track size, allowing all MAX slots to be used. However, the KTU syllabus expects the **sentinel-slot** approach.

## 3.3 Queue Implementation Using Linked Lists (Exhaustive C++ Program)

### 3.3.1 Why Use a Linked List?

- **Dynamic sizing** : No need to declare MAX at compile time.
- **No overflow** : Can grow as long as system memory is available (no fixed cap).
- **Efficient dequeue** : Unlike the array-based linear queue, dequeue is **O(1)** (no shifting required).

### 3.3.2 Full C++ Implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// Node structure for the linked list
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
};

class LinkedListQueue {
private:
    Node* front;
    Node* rear;

public:
    LinkedListQueue() {
        front = NULL;
        rear  = NULL;
    }

    bool isEmpty() {
        return (front == NULL);
    }

    // Enqueue: Insert at the rear (O(1))
    void enqueue(int x) {
        Node* newNode = new Node();
        newNode->data = x;
        newNode->next = NULL;
        if (rear == NULL) {          // Empty queue
            front = rear = newNode;
        } else {
            rear->next = newNode;
            rear = newNode;
        }
        cout << x << " enqueued." << endl;
    }

    // Dequeue: Remove from the front (O(1))
    int dequeue() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Queue Underflow!" << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        Node* temp = front;
        int x = temp->data;
        front = front->next;
        if (front == NULL)           // Queue became empty
            rear = NULL;
        delete temp;
        return x;
    }

    // Peek: Return front element
    int peek() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Queue is empty." << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        return front->data;
    }

    // Display: Traverse from front to rear
    void display() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Queue is empty." << endl;
            return;
        }
        cout << "Linked List Queue: ";
        Node* curr = front;
        while (curr != NULL) {
            cout << curr->data << " ";
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        cout << endl;
    }

    // Destructor: Free all nodes
    ~LinkedListQueue() {
        while (!isEmpty())
            dequeue();
    }
};
```

### 3.3.3 Step-by-Step Trace

Let us trace `enqueue(10)`, `enqueue(20)`, `enqueue(30)`, `dequeue()`, `dequeue()`, `enqueue(40)` on a fresh linked list queue.

| Step | Operation | Linked List State (front → ... → rear) | front ptr | rear ptr |
|------|-----------|----------------------------------------|-----------|----------|
| 1 | enqueue(10) | `10 → NULL` | node(10) | node(10) |
| 2 | enqueue(20) | `10 → 20 → NULL` | node(10) | node(20) |
| 3 | enqueue(30) | `10 → 20 → 30 → NULL` | node(10) | node(30) |
| 4 | dequeue() | `20 → 30 → NULL` | node(20) | node(30) |
| 5 | dequeue() | `30 → NULL` | node(30) | node(30) |
| 6 | enqueue(40) | `30 → 40 → NULL` | node(30) | node(40) |

> **Key Observation:** Enqueue is performed by **appending at the rear** (using `rear->next = newNode`). Dequeue is performed by **removing the front node** and advancing `front`. Both operations are **O(1)**, since we maintain both `front` and `rear` pointers.

## 3.4 Priority Queue Implementation (Exhaustive C++ Programs)

A **priority queue** dequeues elements based on **priority**, not insertion order. The most common implementation strategies in the KTU Module 2 syllabus are:

1. **Unsorted array/linked list** : Easy to enqueue, slow to dequeue.
2. **Sorted array/linked list** : Slow to enqueue, fast to dequeue.
3. **Binary heap** (advanced) : Both operations are O(log n) — covered in higher modules.

### 3.4.1 Implementation Using an Unsorted Array (Simple, Exam-Friendly)

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#define MAX 100
using namespace std;

class PriorityQueue {
private:
    int arr[MAX];
    int size;

public:
    PriorityQueue() { size = 0; }

    bool isEmpty() { return (size == 0); }
    bool isFull()  { return (size == MAX); }

    // Enqueue: Simply append at the end (O(1))
    void enqueue(int x) {
        if (isFull()) {
            cout << "Priority Queue Overflow!" << endl;
            return;
        }
        arr[size++] = x;
        cout << x << " enqueued." << endl;
    }

    // Dequeue: Find the element with highest priority (here: largest value)
    int dequeue() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Priority Queue Underflow!" << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        int maxIdx = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < size; i++) {
            if (arr[i] > arr[maxIdx])    // Higher value = higher priority
                maxIdx = i;
        }
        int x = arr[maxIdx];
        // Shift elements to fill the gap (O(n))
        for (int i = maxIdx; i < size - 1; i++)
            arr[i] = arr[i + 1];
        size--;
        return x;
    }

    void display() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Priority Queue is empty." << endl;
            return;
        }
        cout << "Priority Queue: ";
        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++)
            cout << arr[i] << " ";
        cout << endl;
    }
};
```

### 3.4.2 Step-by-Step Trace (Priority = Element Value, Higher = More Urgent)

Enqueue 10, 40, 20, 30, dequeue, dequeue.

| Step | Operation | Array State | Notes |
|------|-----------|-------------|-------|
| 1 | enqueue(10) | `[10, _, _, _, _]` | size = 1 |
| 2 | enqueue(40) | `[10, 40, _, _, _]` | size = 2 |
| 3 | enqueue(20) | `[10, 40, 20, _, _]` | size = 3 |
| 4 | enqueue(30) | `[10, 40, 20, 30, _]` | size = 4 |
| 5 | dequeue() | `[10, 30, 20, _, _]` | Highest priority (40) removed, elements shifted |
| 6 | dequeue() | `[10, 20, _, _, _]` | Highest priority (30) removed, elements shifted |

> **Result**: Dequeue order = 40, 30, 20, 10 → **NOT** 10, 40, 20, 30. This confirms that **priority overrides arrival order**.

### 3.4.3 Priority Queue with (Element, Priority) Pair Using Sorted Linked List

A more realistic priority queue stores **(data, priority)** pairs, where priority is a **separate integer field**.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

struct PNode {
    int data;
    int priority;
    PNode* next;
};

class SortedPriorityQueue {
private:
    PNode* front;

public:
    SortedPriorityQueue() { front = NULL; }

    bool isEmpty() { return (front == NULL); }

    // Enqueue: Insert in sorted order (descending priority)
    void enqueue(int data, int priority) {
        PNode* newNode = new PNode();
        newNode->data = data;
        newNode->priority = priority;
        newNode->next = NULL;

        // Case 1: Empty queue OR new node has higher priority than front
        if (front == NULL || priority > front->priority) {
            newNode->next = front;
            front = newNode;
        }
        // Case 2: Find correct position
        else {
            PNode* curr = front;
            while (curr->next != NULL && curr->next->priority >= priority)
                curr = curr->next;
            newNode->next = curr->next;
            curr->next = newNode;
        }
        cout << "(" << data << ", P=" << priority << ") enqueued." << endl;
    }

    // Dequeue: Remove the highest-priority element (always at front)
    int dequeue() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Priority Queue Underflow!" << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        PNode* temp = front;
        int x = temp->data;
        front = front->next;
        delete temp;
        return x;
    }

    void display() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Priority Queue is empty." << endl;
            return;
        }
        cout << "Priority Queue (front to rear, highest to lowest priority): ";
        PNode* curr = front;
        while (curr != NULL) {
            cout << "(" << curr->data << ",P=" << curr->priority << ") ";
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
};
```

### 3.4.4 Step-by-Step Trace of Sorted Priority Queue

Enqueue (A, 3), enqueue (B, 5), enqueue (C, 1), enqueue (D, 4), dequeue, dequeue.

| Step | Operation | Sorted List State (front → rear) | Notes |
|------|-----------|----------------------------------|-------|
| 1 | enqueue(A, 3) | `(A,3) → NULL` | First element |
| 2 | enqueue(B, 5) | `(B,5) → (A,3) → NULL` | B has higher priority, becomes front |
| 3 | enqueue(C, 1) | `(B,5) → (A,3) → (C,1) → NULL` | C inserted at the end (lowest priority) |
| 4 | enqueue(D, 4) | `(B,5) → (D,4) → (A,3) → (C,1) → NULL` | D inserted between B and A |
| 5 | dequeue() | `(D,4) → (A,3) → (C,1) → NULL` | Removes B (highest priority) |
| 6 | dequeue() | `(A,3) → (C,1) → NULL` | Removes D (now highest) |

> **Critical Insight:** Because the list is maintained in **sorted (descending) order by priority**, the **dequeue** operation is always **O(1)** — we just remove the front node. The trade-off is that **enqueue** becomes **O(n)** in the worst case, since we may need to traverse the entire list to find the correct insertion point.

## 3.5 Comparative Analysis: All Queue Variants

The following table consolidates the **time complexity**, **advantages**, and **disadvantages** of all four queue variants studied in this module. This is a **high-priority KTU summary**.

| Variant | Enqueue | Dequeue | Peek | Memory | Overflow Possible? | Key Advantage | Key Disadvantage |
|---------|---------|---------|------|--------|--------------------|---------------|------------------|
| **Linear Queue (Array)** | O(1) | O(1) | O(1) | Fixed (MAX) | Yes | Simple to implement | Wastes memory after dequeues |
| **Circular Queue (Array)** | O(1) | O(1) | O(1) | Fixed (MAX) | Yes (only when truly full) | No memory wastage | Loses 1 slot (sentinel) |
| **Linked-List Queue** | O(1) | O(1) | O(1) | Dynamic | No (until memory exhausted) | Grows/shrinks dynamically | Extra memory for pointers |
| **Priority Queue (Unsorted Array)** | O(1) | O(n) | O(1) | Fixed (MAX) | Yes | Fast insertion | Slow deletion (linear search) |
| **Priority Queue (Sorted Array)** | O(n) | O(1) | O(1) | Fixed (MAX) | Yes | Fast deletion | Slow insertion (shifting) |
| **Priority Queue (Sorted Linked List)** | O(n) | O(1) | O(1) | Dynamic | No | Fast deletion, dynamic size | Slow insertion (traversal) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Tip:** When asked to **"compare linear queue and circular queue"** in a 3-mark or 7-mark question, you MUST mention the **memory wastage problem** of the linear queue and explain how the **modulo arithmetic** in the circular queue **reuses freed cells** to solve it.

