## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]
**Define a queue data structure. List any four operations performed on a queue and briefly explain the FIFO principle.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

A **queue** is a linear data structure that follows the **FIFO (First In, First Out)** principle. In a queue, insertion (enqueue) is performed at the **rear** end, and deletion (dequeue) is performed at the **front** end. The element that has been in the queue for the longest time is removed first.

The four principal operations are:
1. **enqueue(x)** : Inserts element *x* at the rear of the queue.
2. **dequeue()** : Removes and returns the element at the front of the queue.
3. **peek() / front()** : Returns the front element without removing it.
4. **isEmpty()** : Returns true if the queue has no elements.

**FIFO Principle**: The element inserted first is the element removed first, just as people in a real-world queue (e.g., a ticket counter line) are served in the order they arrive. *(1 mark for definition, 1 mark for operations list, 1 mark for FIFO explanation.)*

---

### Question 2 [KTU University Exam - May 2024]
**What is a circular queue? Why is it preferred over a linear queue implemented using arrays?**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

A **circular queue** is a variant of the linear queue in which the **last position is connected back to the first position**, forming a logical ring. This is achieved using **modulo arithmetic** on the index pointers.

A linear queue implemented using an array suffers from a **memory wastage problem**: once elements are dequeued from the front, the freed cells at the front of the array **cannot be reused**, because the `rear` pointer only moves forward. Even if there is free space, the queue reports **overflow**.

A circular queue **solves this problem** by allowing the `rear` pointer to **wrap around** to index 0 using the formula `rear = (rear + 1) % MAX`. This way, the freed cells can be reused for new enqueue operations, **maximizing the utilization of the array space**. *(1 mark for circular queue definition, 1 mark for linear queue drawback, 1 mark for circular queue solution.)*

