> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Mark-Loss Pitfalls**
>
> 1. **Resetting `front` and `rear` after queue becomes empty** (array implementation). Many students forget to reset pointers to -1 after the last dequeue, leading to incorrect `isEmpty()` checks in subsequent operations. **Penalty: -1 to -2 marks**.
> 2. **Forgetting modulo `% MAX`** in the circular queue. Students often write `rear = rear + 1` instead of `rear = (rear + 1) % MAX`. This breaks the wrap-around behaviour and is the **most common** 1-mark deduction.
> 3. **Confusing empty and full conditions in circular queue**: Without the sentinel slot, `rear == front` is ambiguous. If you use a `count` variable, clearly mention it; otherwise, use the `(rear + 1) % MAX == front` convention. **Penalty: -1.5 marks** if ambiguous.
> 4. **Memory leak in linked list queue**: Forgetting the `delete temp;` in `dequeue()` causes memory leaks. Even if the program "works" without it, examiners check for proper memory management. **Penalty: -0.5 to -1 mark**.
> 5. **Priority queue: not maintaining sorted order**. In a sorted linked-list priority queue, if you simply append at the end, the dequeue logic will fail because the highest priority is not necessarily at the front. **Penalty: -2 marks** for incorrect ordering.
> 6. **Forgetting edge cases**: Always handle `isEmpty()` and `isFull()` explicitly. Examiners often test programs with an empty queue or a full queue to verify these checks.

