## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid-Revision Checklist (Pin This Before Exams)**

- ✅ **Queue** = Linear, FIFO data structure. Insert at REAR, delete at FRONT.
- ✅ **Enqueue** = O(1), **Dequeue** = O(1) (linked list) or O(n) (array, due to shifting? — actually, with `front` and `rear` pointers, dequeue is **O(1)** for both array and linked list).
- ✅ **Linear Queue Empty**: `front == -1` or `front > rear`. **Full**: `rear == MAX - 1`.
- ✅ **Linear Queue Drawback**: Memory wastage — once dequeued, cells at front cannot be reused.
- ✅ **Circular Queue** uses **modulo arithmetic** to wrap `front` and `rear` indices: `next = (current + 1) % MAX`.
- ✅ **Circular Queue Empty**: `front == -1`. **Full**: `(rear + 1) % MAX == front`.
- ✅ **Circular Queue Size**: `(rear - front + N) % N` where N = MAX.
- ✅ **Circular Queue Loses 1 Slot** (sentinel), so it can hold at most **MAX - 1** elements.
- ✅ **Linked-List Queue** has two pointers: `front` and `rear`. `enqueue` appends at rear (O(1)). `dequeue` removes from front (O(1)). No fixed MAX — grows dynamically.
- ✅ **Linked-List Queue Empty**: `front == NULL`. **Full**: Only when system memory is exhausted.
- ✅ **Priority Queue** dequeues the element with **highest priority** first, regardless of arrival order.
- ✅ **Priority Queue (Unsorted Array)**: enqueue O(1), dequeue O(n) (linear search).
- ✅ **Priority Queue (Sorted Array/List)**: enqueue O(n) (insertion in sorted order), dequeue O(1).
- ✅ **Real-world applications**: CPU scheduling, BFS, print spooling, packet buffering, Huffman coding.
- ✅ **Always handle underflow** (dequeue from empty) and **overflow** (enqueue to full) with explicit checks.
- ✅ **Memory management**: In linked-list queues, always `delete` the dequeued node to prevent memory leaks.

